OPERATIONS
OVERVIEW

In spite
of higher mine and mill throughput at both Greens Creek and Lucky
Friday, silver production decreased slightly in 2010 due to lower
silver ore grades at both operations, which was anticipated.
However, production of lead and zinc, which are important
by-products, increased to record levels in 2010 due to higher
grades and ore volumes. Fourth quarter silver production was higher
compared to a year ago mainly due to higher milled
tonnage.

The key
drivers for the reduction in total cash cost per ounce of silver
year-over-year are higher metals prices and increased production of
gold, lead and zinc. The increase in the fourth quarter total cash
cost per ounce of silver, in comparison to the same period in 2009,
is due to lower zinc and lead grades resulting in lower by-product
credits.

 

 


  


 

 




 



 



 



 



 



 



 



 



 



 



 



 



 






 



 



 



 



 



 



 



